Boil a full #kettle{}.

Trim the @pak choi{1}, then separate the leaves. Cut the @lime{1/2} into wedges.

Trim and peel the @carrot{1}. Use the #peeler{} to peel long ribbons down the length of the carrot, stopping at the core.

Pour the boiled water into a #medium saucepan{} with @salt{1/4%tsp} and bring back to a boil.

When boiling, add the @egg noodle nest{2} and pak choi to the water. Cook until tender, ~{4%minutes}.

Once cooked, drain in a #colander{} and run under cold water to stop the noodles sticking together.

Meanwhile, heat a #large frying pan{} on medium-high heat (no oil).

Once hot, add the @British beef mince{240%g} and fry until browned, ~{5-6%minutes}.

Use a #spoon{} to break it up as it cooks, then drain and discard any excess fat.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw mince.

Once the beef is cooked, turn the heat down to medium.

Add the @ginger, garlic & lemongrass puree{15%g} and fry until fragrant, ~{1%minute}.

Pour in the @sambal paste{15%g}, @teriyaki sauce{75%g} and @water{50%ml}. Stir to combine and simmer until glossy, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Toss the cooked noodles, pak choi and carrot ribbons into the sauce until coated and piping hot, ~{1%minute}.

Add a squeeze of lime juice. Taste and season with salt and pepper if needed.

When ready, share the Vietnamese inspired beef noodles between your #bowls{}.

Serve the remaining lime wedges alongside for squeezing over. Enjoy!